{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}} {{italic title}} {{Infobox Song Contest |name = Best of Eurovision |logo = |final = 20 May 2006 |presenters = [[Thomas Hermanns]]<ref>http://www.mediabiz.de/musik/news/ndr-laeutet-countdown-zum-grand-prix-mit-internet-abstimmung-ein/200616</ref> |exsupervisor = [[Svante Stockselius]] |exproducer = |director = |conductor = |host = [[European Broadcasting Union|EBU]], [[Norddeutscher Rundfunk|NDR]] |venue = [[Norddeutscher_Rundfunk#Studios|NDR Studios]], [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]] |winner = {{unbulleted list|{{Esc|Ukraine|y=2004}}|"[[Wild Dances (single)|Wild Dances]]"}} |vote = Televote, jury vote and online poll. (Germany only) |entries = 19 |debut = |return = |withdraw = |null = |interval = |opening = |reprise = }}
The '''Best of Eurovision (Die Grand Prix Hitliste)''' was a unique one-off contest, held in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], on 20 May 2006. Its aim was to determine the best [[:Category:Eurovision songs|song]] from the [[Eurovision Song Contest]], by means of an [[opinion poll]]. [[List of Eurovision Song Contest winners|Eurovision winners]] and [[Germany in the Eurovision Song Contest|German Eurovision entries]] competed. Only entries from [[Eurovision Song Contest 1960|1960]] to [[Eurovision Song Contest 2005|2005]] were included in the contest.
On the television programme "Best of Eurovision", [[Ruslana|Ruslana's]] "[[Wild Dances]]" was presented as the winner, ahead of famous songs, such as "[[Waterloo (ABBA song)|Waterloo]]" and Germany's "[[Ein bisschen Frieden]]", which finished sixth and twelfth, respectively. The programme was viewed by a television audience of approximately six million people in Germany.<ref name="ruslana">{{cite web |url=http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/6210 |title=Ruslana - The best of Eurovision |last=Busa |first=Alexandru |publisher=''ESCToday'' |date=2007-05-24 |accessdate=2009-02-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090217132322/http://www.esctoday.com/news/read/6210 |archivedate=17 February 2009 |df=dmy }}</ref>
==Participating countries== The top nineteen Eurovision acts voted for in an online poll participated in the live show. No acts were performed live but their original performances in their respective years was shown to viewers instead. After all nineteen songs were shown the voting lines opened by televote and once again via online poll. All votes were combined and counted as the final results. At the end of the show [[Ruslana]] was announced as the winner with a 7251 vote lead over runner-up [[Sertab Erener]].
