{{no footnotes|date=June 2015}}
The '''Coal Glen mine disaster''' was a coal mine explosion that occurred on May 27, 1925, in [[Farmville, Chatham County, North Carolina|Coal Glen]], Oakland Township, [[Chatham County, North Carolina|Chatham County]], [[North Carolina]], United States.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://freepages.history.rootsweb.com/~pfwilson/coal_glen.html|title=Coal Glen Mine Disaster|website=freepages.history.rootsweb.com|access-date=2017-06-27}}</ref> It is located just north of the city of [[Sanford, North Carolina]]. Fifty-three miners died in the explosion. Attempts at re-opening the mine were made sporadically until the 1950s, but were never financially viable. The mine was permanently closed in 1951.
A historical marker was dedicated June 3, 2017 at Farmville Community Church at [[U.S. Route 15/501 in North Carolina|U.S. 15-501]] and Walter Bright Road.
