{{other uses|Nostalgia (disambiguation)}} {{Refimprove|date=July 2010}} {{Infobox holiday |holiday_name = Noche de la Nostalgia |image = |imagesize = |caption = | type = National |official_name = Noche de la Nostalgia |observedby = {{URU}} |scheduling = same day each year |date = 24 August |relatedto = [[dancing]], [[oldies]] }}
In [[Uruguay]], the '''Nostalgia Night''' (Spanish: ''Noche de la Nostalgia'') is celebrated every 24th of August. Every dancing club, broadcasting station and many other events play "nostalgic music" (oldies).
==Overview== Its origins are somehow disputed. It started in the 24 August 1978. According to José Fernández, owner of the Disco Ton Ton Metek, as every 24 August is the day before Uruguayan Independence Day, a national holiday, once he proposed to Pablo Lecueder (director of the broadcast program Old Hits, in the then [[CX32 Radiomundo]]) to do something in a night that could be commercially profitable.
That same year, the 24 August at night (disputed) in Ton Ton was held the first Nostalgia Night. The night repeated its success and become part of Uruguayan folklore.
Uruguayans are said to be typically nostalgic.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.larepublica.com.uy/cultura/53647-el-invento-de-la-nostalgia/|title=The invention of nostalgia |publisher=La República|date=24 August 2001|accessdate=11 July 2013|language=es}}</ref> Be it for that or for whatever reason, the Nostalgia Night is such a success that it was officially named by the Ministry of Tourism.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www0.parlamento.gub.uy/leyes/AccesoTextoLey.asp?Ley=17825&Anchor=|title=Ley Nº 17.825. Se denomina el 24 de agosto de cada año como la "Noche de la nostalgia".|publisher=[[Uruguayan Parliament]]|date=|accessdate=11 July 2013|language=es|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814101815/http://www.parlamento.gub.uy/leyes/AccesoTextoLey.asp?Ley=17825&Anchor=|archivedate=14 August 2011|df=}}</ref>
